Sailormen Inc., a Miami-based Popeyes franchisee with more than 130 restaurants in its portfolio, has filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in the Southern District of Florida.&nbsp;

In its filing, the company estimated it had about $130 million in debt. The company said it has ‚Äúfaced significant challenges‚Äù throughout the past year leading to its financial struggles, including rising operational costs due to inflation and increased borrowing expenses, higher wages, and consumer behavior changes since the pandemic that drove lower traffic.

Additionally, in late 2023, Sailormen entered into an agreement with a buyer, Tar Heels Spice, to sell 16 of its Georgia restaurants as part of a restructuring plan. That deal fell through, however, further straining the company‚Äôs finances. Sailormen stopped covering rent for the locations in April 2024 and then filed a breach of contract lawsuit against Tar Heels Spice in August 2024.&nbsp;

Further, the company‚Äôs primary lender, BMO Bank, filed a lawsuit in December for breach of contract against Sailormen related to the franchisee‚Äôs loan obligations. In that complaint, BMO is seeking a court-appointed receiver to take control of Sailormen and its assets, which was the catalyst for the Chapter 11 filing. Sailormen said its stakeholders ‚Äúwill fare better‚Äù because of the filing.

Sailormen ended 2025 with more than $233 million in sales and a net operating loss of nearly $19 million.&nbsp;

This filing comes on the heels of a relatively soft year for the chain, including -2% same-store sales in the most recently reported third quarter. Those results followed a 0.9% decline in same-store sales in Q2, and -4% in Q1.&nbsp;In 2024, however, Popeyes sales were up nearly 4%, while the company has increased its sales by nearly 20% since 2021.&nbsp;

Several concepts have filed bankruptcy already, less than a month into 2026, illustrating a market rife with challenges such as higher cost inputs and slower consumer usage. Over the past six weeks, concepts including Pieology Pizza, Taste of Belgium, Ray Ray‚Äôs Hog Pit, and Compass Coffee have all filed for protection.&nbsp;

